    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p><i>Clionella taxea</i></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_2575",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Shell large and heavy with long spire and sharp apex. Whorls slightly swollen and covered with a thin, black periostracum that readily flakes off, revealing pinky-white shell beneath. Aperture wide and very characteristic in shape in that the outer lip is cut back into a very deep sinus, matching the similarly deep sinus leading onto the suture. Operculum horny. Specimens from the west are larger and smoother then those from the east of the range.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_2576",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Up to 87 mm in length.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_2577",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to South Africa<i>.</i></p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> False Bay to East London.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_2578",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Rarely found and not featured in most regional field guides. Most specimens trawled in deeper water off the Agulhas Bank, but has been found by SCUBA divers active at night in False Bay.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_2579",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Poorly known, but probably a scavenger.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_2580",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Details unknown, but related species lay purse-shaped eggs capsules with a short stalk and from which crawling young emerge.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_2581",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>The large size and unusual notches in the aperture readily identify this species. The only species with a similar structure is the much smaller (51 mm) <i>C. tripartita, </i>which is only found east of Jeffreys Bay.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_2582",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Kilburn, RN (1985). Turridae (Mollusca: Gastropoda) of southern Africa and Mozambique. Part 2. Subfamily Clavatulinae. <i>Annals of the Natal Museum</i>, 26(2), 417-470.<br><br>Kilburn, R & Rippey, E (1982). Sea Shells of Southern Africa. Macmillan South Africa, Johannesburg (p. 116 as <i>Clionella taxea</i>).<br><br>Steyn, DG & Lussi, M (2005). Offshore Shells of Southern Africa: A pictorial guide to more than 750 Gastropods. Published by the authors (p. 204).",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_2583",
